            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Malia Kouri\u2019s life is a story of two shores. Raised in K\u0101ne\u02bbohe on O\u02bbahu, her world was defined by the scent of plumeria, the embrace of her large K\u0101naka Maoli family, and the spirit of *'ohana*. Her father, a fisherman, taught her respect for the ocean, while her Lebanese-American mother filled their home with a different kind of warmth and spice. Though she cherished her upbringing, a restless, creative energy pulsed within her. She felt the island, for all its beauty, was too small for her ambitions.\n\nAt eighteen, she made the heart-wrenching decision to leave, trading turquoise waters for the fog-laced hills of San Francisco. She enrolled in a Visual Communications program, earning an associate's degree that felt more practical than a four-year bachelor's. She needed to work, to build a life. Malia found her calling not in a quiet studio but in the dynamic world of retail. She discovered a talent for shaping spaces, turning chaotic storefronts into curated sanctuaries of calm and beauty. Her climb was steady, driven by an innate understanding of aesthetics and customer flow, leading to her current role as a Store Experience Manager for a high-end apparel brand downtown.\n\nNow 31, Malia\u2019s life is a carefully composed balance. Her day begins with a pre-dawn stillness in her Inner Richmond apartment before she joins the rumbling rhythm of the 38 Geary bus for her 3.2-mile commute. In San Francisco, she has built a chosen family\u2014a tight-knit group of friends who share potlucks and weekend hikes in the Presidio, offering a mainland version of the community she misses.\n\nHer connection to the city is complex; she thrives on its creative energy but feels a persistent longing for Hawaii's genuine warmth. This feeling fuels her ultimate dream: to open her own lifestyle boutique in the Bay Area, one that exclusively showcases the work of Pacific Islander artists and designers. It would be more than a store; it would be an embassy of culture, a way to finally braid the two halves of her life into a single, beautiful whole."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers the weight of the p\u012bkake lei her father placed over her neck at the airport gate. It was heavier than flowers should be. Each tiny, white blossom was a day she was choosing to miss, a scent she was leaving behind for the sterile, recycled air of the plane. When she finally took it off in her dorm, the petals were already browning. That moment, at eighteen, taught her that every new beginning is paid for with a small, fragrant death. It was the first true cost of her ambition.\n\n2.\nAt twenty, working in a cluttered Hayes Valley boutique, the manager let her re-merchandise a chaotic tabletop. As Malia moved objects, a sense of calm settled over her. She found harmony in the textures and shapes, creating a narrative of calm that wasn't there before. A customer immediately bought a vase she\u2019d placed at the forefront. It was a jolt of validation more powerful than any grade; she realized she didn't need a canvas to create art. She could build sanctuaries for people right where they stood.\n\n3.\nIt was a \"Friendsgiving\" in a cramped NoPa apartment several years ago. Rain lashed against the windows, but inside, the air was warm with the smells of roasted turkey and her own offering of shoyu chicken. Looking around at the loud, laughing circle of her chosen family, she felt a familiar ache in her chest dissolve into warmth. It wasn't the easy, blood-deep comfort of home, but it was real. That night taught her that *'ohana* could be intentionally woven, not just inherited.\n\n4.\nWalking home through the Inner Richmond fog one evening, a restaurant's exhaust fan blew a sweet, greasy cloud of garlic and ginger into her path. For one staggering second, she wasn't on Clement Street; she was in her mother\u2019s K\u0101ne\u02bbohe kitchen, watching her pound spices for a Lebanese marinade. The longing was so sharp it stole her breath. This memory, from when she was twenty-seven, affirmed that San Francisco could never fully have her. Part of her would always be an ocean away, beckoned by a ghost of garlic.\n\n5.\nLast year, while meticulously folding a $400 beige sweater at work, a colleague sighed about finding \"authentic\" decor for her apartment. In that instant, Malia pictured the koa bowls and vibrant lauhala weavings of her childhood. The contrast between the sterile luxury she sold and the living art she knew was jarring. It was no longer a vague homesickness but a clear, driving mission. Her two worlds didn't have to be separate. She could build the bridge herself, and that bridge would be her store."
